2. Decision tree algorithms

In this seciton, we learn three different decision tree algorithms.

  • CART (Breiman’s decision tree)
  • conditional inference tree (Hothorn’s decision tree)

2.1. CART

CART (classification and regression tree) was proposed by Breiman et al. (1984). Although some decision tree algorithms had already been proposed earlier than their work, their work made tree algorithms useful. The key finding was so-called “pruning” method, which takes the balance between complexity and accuracy.

Here make a regression formula, y1 is regressed by the set of predictors x1-x16.
Similarly, a classification problem can be tested by replacing y1 by y2 (but it is skipped in this workshop)

# creating formula
formula.1 = as.formula(paste("y1", paste(colnames(df)[2:length(colnames(df))], collapse=" + "), sep=" ~ ")) 
print(formula.1)
## y1 ~ x1 + x2 + x3 + x4 + x5 + x6 + x7 + x8 + x9 + x10 + x11 + 
##     x12 + x13 + x14 + x15 + x16

Modeling part. For regression use method=“anova”; for classification, use method=“class”

# regression
cart.1 = rpart(formula.1, data=df, method="anova",control=rpart.control(minsplit=10, cp=0.001))
Option Description
method
class method for a classification tree
anova method for a regression tree
control
minsplit minimum number of observations in a node before attempting a split
cp cost complexity factor. a split must decrease the overall lack of fit by a factor of cp before being attempted.

Note that you can change the two parameters! These parameters are so-called hyper-parameters because model per se is nonparametric, but the algorithm has the parameters, which can influence results.
But how? One option is to find the best model using cross validation. Let’s check how cp affects model performance.


Firstly, CART algorithm splits data as much as possible, unless minsplit is met. At the top, x7 at the value of 8.2 was selected to split the dataset into two. Each of the circles (terminal node) represents an expected value of the response variable, conditioned by a set of predictors and their threshold values.

prp(cart.1) # plot with rpart.plot package

Yet, the tree is unnecessary complex and overfits to the data. So, we want to simplify the tree structure by pruning (cutting) some (too detailed) brunches, while keeping model performance. Cross-validation is the key to find how much we can prune the tree.

plotcp(cart.1)  #plot cross-validation results

rsq.rpart(cart.1)   #plot approximate R-squared and relative error for different splits (2 plots). labels are only appropriate for the "anova" method.

cp.best = cart.1$cptable[which(cart.1$cptable[,"xerror"]==min(cart.1$cptable[,"xerror"])),"CP"]

Now, we found cp=0.0098657 the best for balancing complexity and accuracy (note that the performance even improved by reducing overfitting!). Let’s compare the best and original tree structures.

# regression (y1) and classification (y2)
cart.1.best = rpart(formula.1, data=df, method="anova",control=rpart.control(minsplit=10, cp=cp.best)) 

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
prp(cart.1.best)
prp(cart.1)

You can also play with changing minsplit. This is another hyperparameter.




2.2. Conditional inference tree

Conditional inference tree is another tree-based algorithm developed relatively recently by Hothorn et al. (2006). They found that, if the data must be split more or not can be determined based on statistical significance, and by doing so the structure of a tree can be much simplified while the performance does not significantly reduce from the model selected based on CART CV-technique.
We use party package:

ctree.1 = ctree(formula.1, df, control = ctree_control(testtype = "Bonferroni", mincriterion = 0.95, minsplit = 10, minbucket = 7))
plot(ctree.1)

If testtype is “Univariate”, p-value correction is not peformed, so more predictors can appear. If implementing correction or not is always difficult, as it is a trade-off of Type 1 & 2 error.

ctree.2 = ctree(formula.1, df, control = ctree_control(testtype = "Univariate", mincriterion = 0.95, minsplit = 10, minbucket = 7))
plot(ctree.2)




3. Random Forest algorithm & interpretation

In this seciton, we learn a random forest algorithm based on conditional inference tree.

The RF algorithm based on conditional inference tree is developed in the package party. While we can use the package, let’s learn another useful package, mlr, which is an integrative tool for machine learning algorithms.
In this section, we learn the followings:


  • modeling with RF
  • parameter tuning
  • interpretation: variable importance
  • visualization: partial dependence (PD) plot and individual conditional expectation (ICE) plot





mlr can allow parallel computing. The number is the number of cores used.

parallelStartSocket(3)
## Starting parallelization in mode=socket with cpus=3.

Model set up

regr.task = makeRegrTask(data = df, target = "y1")
regr.learner.cforest = makeLearner(cl="regr.cforest", predict.type = "response")
model.cforest = train(regr.learner.cforest, regr.task)

Model performance can be evaluated using various indicators.

pred.cforest = predict(model.cforest, task = regr.task)
listMeasures(regr.task)
##  [1] "featperc"    "mae"         "mape"        "medse"       "msle"       
##  [6] "rae"         "spearmanrho" "timeboth"    "timetrain"   "rmsle"      
## [11] "timepredict" "medae"       "sse"         "expvar"      "kendalltau" 
## [16] "rmse"        "mse"         "rrse"        "sae"         "rsq"        
## [21] "arsq"
performance(pred.cforest, measures = list(mse, rsq))
##        mse        rsq 
## 11.2242302  0.5102861



Cross validation

To check the stability of the model, we can use cross-validation.

We can see the reduction of the performance from the model fitting. aggr shows the averages from the independent k-fold tests (measures.test).

cv.cforest$aggr
## mse.test.mean rsq.test.mean 
##    17.2855779     0.2399196
cv.cforest$measures.test
##   iter      mse       rsq
## 1    1 16.74682 0.1669095
## 2    2 17.57950 0.2756194
## 3    3 17.53042 0.2772299



RF algorithms have two hyper-parameters which need to be tuned. This could be computationally expensive, so various efficient optimizaiton algorithms have been proposed and implemented in mlr.

Today, let’s use the simplest one:

Let’s keep the best model.

model.cforest.best = train(setHyperPars(makeLearner("regr.cforest"), par.vals = tune.cforest$x),regr.task)



We can visualize how these hyper-parameters affect to model performance. Ideally, the larger mtry and ntree, the lower error, in this example.

plotHyperParsEffect(generateHyperParsEffectData(tune.cforest), x = "ntree", y = "mtry", z = "mse.test.mean",
  plot.type = "heatmap")



Variable importance measure

vimp = generateFilterValuesData(regr.task, method = "cforest.importance")
plotFilterValues(vimp)

We realize that only a few variables are important (x1,x4,x7…). It is worth trying variable selection, removing noisy variables to improve the model performance. Let’s say, we use only the top 5 important variables in RF modeling.

lrn = makeFilterWrapper(learner = "regr.cforest", 
  fw.method = "cforest.importance", fw.abs = 5)
r = resample(learner = lrn, task = regr.task, resampling = rdesc, show.info = FALSE, models = TRUE)
## Exporting objects to slaves for mode socket: .mlr.slave.options
## Mapping in parallel: mode = socket; cpus = 3; elements = 3.
r$aggr
## mse.test.mean 
##      15.96461

We can see the performance is better than the tuned model. We may wonder how to set up the number of variables to use (in this case we just use 5 as an example). There are several variable selection algorithms proposed, and we can also use the tuning function makeParamSet to find the best parameter set of ntree, mtry, and fw.abs.





Partial dependence (PD) plot and Individual Conditional Expectation (ICE) plot

Both plot tools are useful when we want to understand the inside of the RF model. These tools can visualize how a particular variable was used to predict the response variable:

pd = generatePartialDependenceData(model.cforest.best, regr.task, "x9", individual = F)
## Mapping in parallel: mode = socket; cpus = 3; elements = 1.
plotPartialDependence(pd)

Note that if we want to plot all variables, we do not specify it.

pd.all = generatePartialDependenceData(model.cforest.best, regr.task, individual = F)
## Mapping in parallel: mode = socket; cpus = 3; elements = 16.
plotPartialDependence(pd.all)
## Warning in melt.data.table(data.table(obj$data), id.vars = colnames(obj

PD plot is the overall avarage taken from ICE plot. ICE plot is useful particularly when we look for interaction. If we find some patterns of lines, we can expect the predictor interacts with another predictor.

ice = generatePartialDependenceData(model.cforest.best, regr.task, "x9", individual = T)
## Mapping in parallel: mode = socket; cpus = 3; elements = 1.
plotPartialDependence(ice)

ice.all = generatePartialDependenceData(model.cforest.best, regr.task, individual = T)
## Mapping in parallel: mode = socket; cpus = 3; elements = 16.
plotPartialDependence(ice.all)
